A parabolic dish, a tracking device, and a receiver make up a Dish-Stirling Solar Thermal System (DSTS). All of the heat energy that the parabolic dish receives is reflected and focused on the receiver. The working fluids are heated by the concentrated energy, and the Stirling engine is hence powered. By converting thermal energy into rotational energy, this engine generates electrical energy via driving the squirrel-cage induction generator (SCIG). Equation (4) represents the DSTS’s transfer function (Trfn)45.4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
